# Best Practices for Teaching with micro:bit

#### Physical computing is a fun and hands-on way to engage students in coding, however, there are some things to consider to make sure your lessons run smoothly. 



## Organization/set up tips

<img src="https://images.code.org/8c5598c604dc9e7a0e4edcf01d5b7244-image-1707322034881.png" alt="storage container for micro:bit" width="250px" style="border-radius:10px; float:right; margin: 0 40px 80px 40px;">

- #### Labeling the micro:bit is a simple way to assign them to people and count them in and out.

- #### Use the original anti-static pouch to store the micro:bits to protect the device.

- #### Remind students to be gentle when handling their micro:bit. Only handle the  micro:bit by its edges and avoid touching the components when the power is running.

- #### To store multiple micro:bits, there exists a multitude of creative options. Containers can be purchased from a supermarket  perfect to store micro:bits, batteries, cases, USB leads and peripherals like speakers and all-important stickers!
---


<img src="https://images.code.org/f97e7a0677c60156fdd380843c4fc2ea-image-1707322374547.png" alt="micro:bit on a shoe with a one on it" width="250px" style="border-radius:10px; float:right; margin: 0 40px 0px 40px;">

## Relate to familiar concepts 



- #### Use everyday examples to explain the concepts of inputs and outputs in a way that is relatable to their experiences

- #### Review coding concepts like events and loops that have been learned in class and remind students that these concepts carry over to help them code their micro:bits. 

- #### Provide a real-world context or scenario where the micro:bit can be used. For example, creating a temperature sensor to measure the weather or a step counter for fitness.

<br>

